{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508583"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.24,0.36,0.24,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40669"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital after being rescued from a burning house. He reports re-entering the house to save his pet dog and tripping over burning carpet in the living room. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 90/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and Glasgow Coma Scale score is 14/15. His airway appears clear and he is speaking clearly. He weighs 34 kg. He has mixed partial and full-thickness burns on his lower torso, knees, and legs, estimated to cover 20% of his total body surface area. The nearest tertiary burns hospital is three hours away. He has been given appropriate analgesia and an intravenous line has been inserted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange transfer to the regional Burns Unit","Prepare for endotracheal intubation to secure the airway","Fluid resuscitation with 0.9% normal saline + 5% glucose","Start intravenous fluid at a rate of 128 mL/hr","Fasciotomy for the circumferential leg burns"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a child with significant burns (20% TBSA) in a rural setting, requiring immediate management and transfer to a tertiary burns centre. The most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart intravenous fluid at a rate of 128 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E. This is based on the modified Parkland formula, which is crucial for fluid resuscitation in burns patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe modified Parkland formula for children is 3 mL/kg/%TBSA over 24 hours, with half given in the first 8 hours. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor this 34 kg child with 20% TBSA burns, the calculation is: 3 mL \u00d7 34 kg \u00d7 20% = 2040 mL total over 24 hours. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1020 mL should be given in the first 8 hours (2040/2). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHourly rate for first 8 hours: 1020 mL / 8 = 128 mL/hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging transfer to the regional Burns Unit\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary but not the immediate priority. Initial stabilisation and fluid resuscitation should be started before transfer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreparing for endotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if there are signs of inhalation injury or airway compromise. However, the patient currently has a clear airway and is speaking clearly, so this is not the immediate priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid resuscitation with 0.9% normal saline + 5% glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While fluid resuscitation is crucial, Hartmann\u0027s solution or normal saline without glucose is preferred for burns resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciotomy for the circumferential leg burns\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. Fasciotomies are only performed for circumferential full-thickness burns causing neurovascular compromise, and ideally should be done in a Burns Unit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating fluid resuscitation, other important steps include continuous monitoring, pain management, wound care, and arranging transfer to a tertiary burns centre. Inhalation injury should be suspected in all patients rescued from house fires, even if initial examination is reassuring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Burns \u003E10% total body surface area (TBSA) in children should be managed at a major burns centre.","Inhalation injury should always be suspected in patients rescued from house fires.","Fluid resuscitation using the modified Parkland formula is crucial in managing significant burns."],"references":["Burns. In: Royal Childrens Hospital Clinical Guidelines [online]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Burns/","Greenhalgh DG. Management of Burns. N Engl J Med 2019; 380:2349-59. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1807442"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40669"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40669"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T20:58:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T20:59:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"des